# Container / Docker Tutorial

This document covers everything related to running cybernetics-agent in Docker:
the image layout, the compose stack, deployment steps, day-to-day operations,
and the branding state of the container assets.

---

## 1. Files in this repo

| Path                         | Purpose                                                                 |
| ---------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `Dockerfile`                 | Main image build (Debian 13 + s6-overlay + Node 22 + uv/Python 3.13)    |
| `docker-compose.yml`         | Default stack (Linux/macOS, host networking)                            |
| `docker-compose.windows.yml` | Windows Docker Desktop variant (no host networking, explicit ports)     |
| `.dockerignore`              | Excludes `.git`, `node_modules`, `tests/`, `website/`, `apps/`, etc.    |
| `docker/`                    | Runtime supervision scripts (s6 services, stage2 hook, exec shim, etc.) |
| `scripts/test/Dockerfile.install-test` | Test image used by the install-script test harness            |

The `docker/` directory contains:

- `entrypoint.sh` — legacy entrypoint (kept for reference; image uses s6 `/init`)
- `main-wrapper.sh` — the actual ENTRYPOINT target; routes args, drops to the
  `hermes` user via `s6-setuidgid`, exec's the final program
- `hermes-exec-shim.sh` — `docker exec` privilege-drop shim, installed at
  `/opt/hermes/bin/hermes` so commands written under `$HERMES_HOME` stay
  owned by the unprivileged runtime user
- `stage2-hook.sh` — UID/GID remap, volume chown, config seeding, skills sync
  (runs as `cont-init.d/01-hermes-setup`)
- `cont-init.d/015-supervise-perms` — fixes service permissions before start
- `cont-init.d/02-reconcile-profiles` — re-creates per-profile gateway
  s6 services after a restart (the `/run/service/` scandir is tmpfs)
- `s6-rc.d/` — declared s6 services: main process + dashboard

