## 5. Deploy — step by step

### 5.1 Prerequisites

- Docker Engine 24+ with Compose v2 (`docker compose version`)
- ~3–5 GB free for the image (Node 22 + Playwright Chromium + Python deps)
- `~/.hermes` directory on the host (becomes `/opt/data` inside)

### 5.2 Set UID/GID

So container-created files stay owned by your host user:

```sh
export HERMES_UID=$(id -u)
export HERMES_GID=$(id -g)
```

Without these, the container falls back to UID/GID 10000 — fine, but host
ownership will look unusual.

### 5.3 Pre-create the host volume

```sh
mkdir -p ~/.hermes
```

### 5.4 Build the image

```sh
docker compose build
```

Cold build = several minutes. Subsequent builds reuse cached layers unless
`pyproject.toml`, `uv.lock`, or `package*.json` changed.

To bake the git SHA into the image:

```sh
docker compose build --build-arg HERMES_GIT_SHA=$(git rev-parse HEAD)
```

### 5.5 Start the stack

```sh
docker compose up -d
```

This launches:

- `gateway` — main agent (`gateway run`) under s6-overlay supervision
- `dashboard` — web UI on `127.0.0.1:9119`, `depends_on: gateway`

Both use `network_mode: host`, so no `-p` mappings are required.

### 5.6 Verify

```sh
docker compose ps
docker compose logs -f gateway
```

Watch for s6 stage2 init followed by service startup. The gateway should
report ready within ~10 seconds on warm starts.

### 5.7 Access the dashboard

- Local: `http://127.0.0.1:9119`
- Remote: SSH tunnel — `ssh -L 9119:localhost:9119 user@host`. **Never**
  bind `0.0.0.0` without putting an authenticating proxy in front.

