## 6. Day-to-day operations

```sh
# Run a CLI command inside the container (uses the privilege-drop shim)
docker compose exec gateway hermes <subcommand>

# Restart just the gateway (dashboard stays up)
docker compose restart gateway

# Tail logs from both services
docker compose logs -f

# Stop the stack; ~/.hermes persists on the host
docker compose down

# Pull a new published image and recreate (registry workflow only)
docker compose pull && docker compose up -d
```

The `hermes-exec-shim.sh` at `/opt/hermes/bin/hermes` (earliest on `PATH`)
auto-drops privileges from root to the unprivileged runtime user when
called via `docker exec`. This keeps files written under `/opt/data`
from ending up root-owned and unreadable to the supervised services.
Opt out with `HERMES_DOCKER_EXEC_AS_ROOT=1` if you really need root.

